1 A RESOLUTION
2 To express the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death of Leotha "Leo"
3 Bolden.
4 WHEREAS, it is with immense sadness and profound regret that the House of
5 Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana has learned of the passing, on March 25,
6 2026, of Leotha "Leo" Bolden; and
7 WHEREAS, Leotha Bolden was born on August 11, 1950, in Indianola, Mississippi,
8 to Gerdie White and Thomas Jefferson Bolden; he was the twin of his brother, Leon, and the
9 ninth of twelve children; and
10 WHEREAS, Leo accepted Christ at an early age at Big Morning Star Church, and
11 his faith was a foundational aspect of his life; he was a devoted and faithful member of
12 Progressive Baptist Church, where he served with humility, dedication, and love for forty-
13 five years; and
14 WHEREAS, Mr. Bolden was ordained a deacon under the leadership of Pastor Lloyd
15 Joiner, Jr., and faithfully carried out this calling for more than thirty years; in January 2026,
16 Pastor Chad E. Nora honored him with the distinguished title of deacon emeritus; he served
17 as chairman of the church's deacon board and extended his service to the trustee board,
18 Brotherhood Ministry, Sunday school, L.I.N.K.I.E.S. Ministry, counting team, and Prison
19 Ministry; and
20 WHEREAS, Mr. Bolden graduated from Gentry High School and earned a bachelor
21 of science degree in political science from Mississippi Valley State University; he began his
